WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:04.440
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:06.730 --> 00:00:10.796
&gt;&gt; It's my pleasure to introduce
the author who respects food,

00:00:11.740 --> 00:00:15.673
who respects his customers and
respects local Washington DC.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:17.673
Spike Mendelsohn has written The
Good Stuff Cookbook, it's as warm

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:21.410
and friendly, family friendly as
his restaurants, so please welcome

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:25.113
to the National Book
Festival, Spike Mendelsohn.

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:29.240
[ Applause ]

00:00:30.690 --> 00:00:32.023
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:33.406
&gt;&gt; Thank you, thank you very much.

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:36.806
It's an honor to be here.

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:39.830
You know, if you asked me a couple
of years ago if I thought I'd be

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:44.256
up here being presented as an author
I'd probably say, you know, no.

00:00:45.550 --> 00:00:49.083
You know, I'm a chef at heart
and I've been very lucky

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:51.346
in the past couple of years.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:53.146
For those who don't know,

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:54.356
I obviously film the reality
TV show called Top Chef.

00:00:56.070 --> 00:00:56.536
Are there any Top Chef
fans out there?

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:00.870
Wooh! You know, we have
an all star season.

00:01:00.940 --> 00:01:04.473
We just got them filming,
so that was really exciting.

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:05.580
I just got back yesterday
from New York.

00:01:06.980 --> 00:01:08.913
It was really, really intense

00:01:08.980 --> 00:01:09.633
and it should be a great
season for you guys.

00:01:11.260 --> 00:01:11.370
But, you know, after filming
the show, I wanted to open

00:01:14.750 --> 00:01:19.083
up a restaurant that, you know,
was very fast, casual and kind of,

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:20.510
you know, gave [audio cut]
that watched the show,

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:24.256
so I didn't really want to open
up a fine dining restaurant with,

00:01:26.270 --> 00:01:26.610
you know, tasting menus
and you know 20 seats.

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:30.530
I really wanted to open up
a restaurant that I can kind

00:01:30.930 --> 00:01:35.196
of invite everybody in and focusing
on classic American food and,

00:01:35.750 --> 00:01:35.816
you know, just doing it really,

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:38.150
really well like taking
the hamburger

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:41.616
and just making it something
a little bit healthier to eat,

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:43.683
something really super fresh.

00:01:43.750 --> 00:01:45.093
And, you know, with a lot
of luck and a great location

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:48.473
on Capitol Hill, you
know, we did that.

00:01:48.730 --> 00:01:50.293
We opened up Good Stuff Eatery
about 2 and a half years ago.

00:01:51.100 --> 00:01:51.163
You know for the-- who-- how
many people have been there?

00:01:54.770 --> 00:01:55.770
Yeah? Wooh.

00:01:57.410 --> 00:01:58.410
That's only half of you, so the
rest-- the other half of you,

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:01.476
I expect you to walk up
the hill a little later

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:04.010
and check the place out.

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:05.806
You know, and the great part
about this concept is is

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:08.433
that it really kind of--
you know, I was new to DC.

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:10.830
I was very worried
leaving New York City

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:13.343
to come open up a restaurant in DC.

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:15.356
You know, I didn't have
too many roots here.

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:18.533
My sister had lived on the
Hill for a couple of years.

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:24.793
But the greatest thing about DC and
Capitol Hill especially is the sense

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:30.056
of community I've developed
over the last 2 and half years.

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:37.573
[Inaudible] You know, I owe most of
my success obviously to my customers

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:38.910
and the people that support
me on the Hill and it's just--

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:41.310
it's been an amazing
ride and, you know,

00:02:43.350 --> 00:02:44.360
we came out with the idea doing
The Good Stuff Cookbook because,

00:02:46.540 --> 00:02:51.206
you know, at Good Stuff Eatery it's
very family focused, it's very farm

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:52.543
to table focused and it's just
like a great feeling and great vibe

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:57.130
when you go to the restaurant.

00:02:57.130 --> 00:02:58.210
And I kind of just want to
share that with everybody

00:02:59.450 --> 00:03:01.070
that didn't have a chance to come
to DC and come to the restaurant,

00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:03.830
and that's why we came up
with the Good Stuff Cookbook.

00:03:04.230 --> 00:03:06.830
So, you know, it's
the whole entire menu

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.133
at Good Stuff plus
another 150 recipes.

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:15.200
The great thing about the book is
I draw, you know, our inspiration

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:21.413
from a lot of my friends and you see
that because a lot of recipes there

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:25.673
that [audio cut] to it and I
think that's the greatest thing

00:03:27.130 --> 00:03:28.130
about the book.

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:29.596
And, you know, it's
also-- it's very--

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:33.756
you know, the cookbook that we came
out with was very easy to shop for.

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:34.113
So, any of you can find
any of these ingredients

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:35.740
at any local supermarket and,
you know, at a minimal price

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:41.313
and just come up with
a great fun meal.

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:43.113
And, you know, the most
important thing about the book is

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:43.530
to get people involved
and invite friends over

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:46.276
and for everyone's
hands to get dirty.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:53.383
So we're really happy with the Good
Stuff Cookbook and now I'm an author

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:54.926
so I could check that
one off on my list.

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:56.396
You know, are there any
questions out there?

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:02.790
I mean, I'd like to keep this
open to questions and-- yes.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:05.443
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:04:06.110 --> 00:04:07.576
&gt;&gt; It turns into soup.

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:12.270
I'm so happy you asked
me that question.

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:15.003
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:16.236
&gt;&gt; Okay, I was told to direct to
the microphone where there's two

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:21.170
on each side for questions.

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:23.170
Although the question was--

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.170
she's saying that my recipe

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:27.760
for my toasted marshmallow milkshake
does not work in the cookbook.

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:27.400
But-- no, no, I was just kidding.

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:32.626
You know the funny thing
is that it's kind of--

00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:39.180
if you're using a Vita-Prep at home,
you're creating friction and heat

00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:40.396
because it's not really made
to kind of spin milkshakes.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:43.623
At the restaurant we use the
old school Hamilton Beach

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:46.913
that has a prong that doesn't
kind of create friction.

00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:50.156
You know, the best thing I
could tell you is probably leave

00:04:52.430 --> 00:04:52.993
out the milk and just work
it just with the ice cream,

00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:56.500
like melted ice cream and
then the toasted marshmallows

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:02.166
and then just blend that together
and then it won't get it soupy.

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:07.450
Yeah, okay.

00:05:08.450 --> 00:05:13.050
&gt;&gt; I enjoy cooking but my interests
and my creativity waxes and wanes.

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:16.300
How do you maintain your
creativity and interest?

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:19.540
&gt;&gt; That's a great question.

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:24.896
You know, I maintain my creativity
and interest and I just keep it--

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:26.713
and for me, for myself, I keep
it really, really seasonal

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:28.956
and I get inspired by
many different things.

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:31.786
You know, I was in Europe
for the last week and I got

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:35.286
to go eat around everywhere.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:36.076
And everywhere I kind of went I
got inspired by a certain type

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:39.950
of ingredients or flavor, so I
was like, "Oh, maybe I could--

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:43.253
you know, maybe I can do that at
Good Stuff Eatery, or maybe I can do

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:44.900
that with a pizza or apply that."

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:47.336
But you know, I also-- you know, I'm
standing here alone but, you know,

00:05:50.730 --> 00:05:54.730
I have a huge support group in
the restaurant and it composes

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:56.276
of my parents, my sister and
a couple of my best friends

00:05:58.190 --> 00:06:01.323
that I kind of forced to
move from New York City

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:01.810
to come open my restaurants with me.

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:03.610
And you know, it's just kind of--

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:06.276
sitting around the table
shooting ideas out,

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:07.760
and I think we mostly relate
on our experiences of travel.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:12.963
You know, when we're coming out
with new menus and we're trying

00:06:12.890 --> 00:06:14.003
to be creative, we always kind
of look back on, you know,

00:06:15.510 --> 00:06:20.043
first like where we've worked, what
molded us to be that type of chef

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:20.776
and then through, you know, our
travels through Europe or Asia

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:26.636
or even New York for
instance and kind

00:06:26.670 --> 00:06:26.976
of what we've picked
up along the way.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:29.973
So, you know, for me it's just like
life is just an inspiration everyday

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:32.513
and I kind of apply that towards
food and what I do, so thank you.

00:06:36.660 --> 00:06:37.660
Yeah.

