&gt;&gt; Where is the hat?

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:42.773
&gt;&gt; The hat, the hat.

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:45.040
I have to ditch the hat.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:48.306
I'm trying to grow out
my hair a little bit.

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:51.293
[Laughter] I hope it looks good.

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:54.160
I don't know.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:57.363
You know it's-- I've been wearing
a hat straight for maybe about 2

00:06:57.290 --> 00:07:01.490
and a half years and I just went
on the all star show and I kind

00:07:02.390 --> 00:07:02.463
of wanted to move myself
out of the hat

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:05.250
because I do get that
question a lot.

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:07.116
But I still have plenty of fedoras

00:07:08.850 --> 00:07:10.446
and I will be wearing
throughout my life but I just feel

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:11.316
like I need my head to
breathe a little bit this day,

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:16.390
so I got a lot going on [inaudible].

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:18.546
&gt;&gt; I'm embarrassed I haven't
been to your restaurant yet

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:19.963
but I've read all about it,
and can you talk a little bit

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:25.183
about the meat that you use--

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:26.250
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:27.983
&gt;&gt; Do you get it locally
and [inaudible]--

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:30.583
&gt;&gt; Yeah, absolutely.

00:07:31.250 --> 00:07:33.783
So, you know, we get everything at
Good Stuff within a hundred miles.

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:34.433
You know, our meat is out of the
farm in Virginia, it's grass fed.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:37.053
You know, I have a-- you know,
that's the greatest thing here also

00:07:40.080 --> 00:07:40.836
for me and I think I owe a
lot of my success to it is

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:43.053
that I have really great
relationship with all my farmers

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:47.116
and my purveyors and the
people that supply me the food.

00:07:49.070 --> 00:07:52.003
And, you know, we're
not buying cheap things,

00:07:52.470 --> 00:07:56.803
so you know they really allow me
to work on the prices of the food

00:07:57.510 --> 00:07:59.443
that I get from them and then

00:07:59.510 --> 00:08:00.360
so I can offer something
reasonably priced for the clientele.

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:05.126
So-- yeah, and my meat's
my own blend.

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:05.346
You know, I spent maybe about 3
months traveling to different farms,

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:13.620
visiting different butchers and
kind of creating my own meat.

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:17.050
It's a little bit of short
rib chuck and sirloin.

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:20.180
It's about 75 percent
to 25 percent fat.

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:25.036
And it's uniquely ours so--
you know, I really enjoy it.

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:26.856
I think it's tasty.

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:29.590
I think it's got great flavor.

00:08:29.590 --> 00:08:30.723
The most important thing
to me about our meat is

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:33.056
that you can just really
apply salt and pepper to it,

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:35.390
give it a really nice sear,

00:08:35.590 --> 00:08:36.790
proper cooking technique
and it's just delicious.

00:08:37.590 --> 00:08:39.030
I'm not one of the guys who like,
you know, folding shallots or butter

00:08:40.750 --> 00:08:41.506
or blue cheese into the meat
or any kind of that, you know,

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:46.726
sauteing onions, just
a personal preference,

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:49.400
but our meat comes from Virginia.

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:51.413
Which way am I going here?

